# Internationalization (i18n) Guidelines

Flash Snap implements full internationalization (i18n) using i18next and react-i18next. All user-facing text must be internationalized to support multiple languages.

## Core Principles
- **NO hardcoded text**: Never use static strings directly in components
- **Always use translation keys**: All text must use the `t()` function from react-i18next
- **Follow the nested structure**: Follow the established organization in locale files

## Implementation
```typescript
// Import the hook at the top of your component
import { useTranslation } from 'react-i18next'

// Use it within your component
const ExampleComponent = () => {
  const { t } = useTranslation()

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>{t('section.title')}</h1>
      <p>{t('section.description')}</p>

      {/* For dynamic content */}
      <span>{t('common.itemCount', { count: items.length })}</span>

      {/* For text with HTML */}
      <div dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html: t('section.htmlContent') }} />
    </div>
  )
}
```

## Locale Structure
Translations are organized hierarchically in the locale files:
- [src/renderer/src/i18n/locales/en-US.ts](mdc:src/renderer/src/i18n/locales/en-US.ts)
- [src/renderer/src/i18n/locales/pt-BR.ts](mdc:src/renderer/src/i18n/locales/pt-BR.ts)

Follow this structure when adding new texts:
1. Group related translations by feature/component
2. Use descriptive keys that indicate the text's purpose
3. Add the same keys to ALL locale files
4. Use common.* namespace for shared/reused texts

## Adding New Translations
When adding new features:
1. First add all keys to the primary locale (en-US)
2. Then add the same keys to all other locales
3. Run the app and check all supported languages

## Pluralization
Use the `count` parameter for pluralized content:
```typescript
t('common.card', { count: 1 }) // "card"
t('common.card', { count: 5 }) // "cards"
```

Remember that all user-facing text must be internationalized to maintain a consistent experience across all supported languages.

